{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e423a145-7888-4db7-8d08-2eabd19598c2","content":"In .NET MAUI, those `Application`-level overrides are replaced by **Window lifecycle events**. You hook into them by overriding `CreateWindow` or using the `Window` events directly:\n\n```csharp\npublic partial class App : Application\n{\n    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n    {\n        var window = new Window(new AppShell());\n\n        window.Created += (s, e) => { /* equivalent to OnStart */ };\n        window.Stopped += (s, e) => { /* equivalent to OnSleep */ };\n        window.Resumed += (s, e) => { /* equivalent to OnResume */ };\n        window.Destroying += (s, e) => { /* cleanup */ };\n\n        return window;\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Mapping summary:**\n\n| Xamarin.Forms | .NET MAUI (Window event) |\n|--------------|--------------------------|\n| `OnStart()`  | `Window.Created`         |\n| `OnSleep()`  | `Window.Stopped`         |\n| `OnResume()` | `Window.Resumed`         |\n\nYou can also access more granular platform-specific lifecycle events via `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs` if needed (e.g., Android's `OnActivityResult`, iOS's `SceneDidEnterBackground`).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ffcd3293-d7c9-46af-85d2-bb877482cdce","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI, specifically about the lifecycle methods OnStart, OnSleep, and OnResume that were overridden in the Application class in Xamarin.Forms.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the lifecycle model changed. Instead of overriding those methods directly on the Application class, MAUI uses a cross-platform lifecycle events system through the `Window` class or by hooking into platform-specific lifecycle events.\n\nLet me provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":459,"requestId":"A84A:6D183:65B741:75F34B:69FBE31A"},"id":"097fb5c1-750b-4757-89e8-8ab920390562","timestamp":"2026-05-07T00:56:03.711Z","parentId":"996bed5b-8bba-4720-b878-a9be1aaa38f9"}
